<p>In <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Baseball" title=3D"Baseball"=
>baseball</a>, <b>batting average</b> (<b>BA</b>) is determined by dividing=
 a player's <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hits_(baseball)" class=
=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Hits (baseball)">hits</a> by their total <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/At-bats" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"A=
t-bats">at-bats</a>. It is usually rounded to three decimal places and read=
 without the decimal: A player with a batting average of .300 is said to be=
 "batting three hundred". If necessary to break ties, batting averages coul=
d be taken beyond the .001 measurement.  In this context, .001 is considere=
d a "point", such that a .235 batter is five points higher than a .230 batt=
er.
</p>
<meta property=3D"mw:PageProp/toc">
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"History">History</h2><span =
class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a =
href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DBatting_average_(baseb=
