iv>
<figure class=3D"mw-default-size mw-halign-right" typeof=3D"mw:File/Thumb">=
<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:National_League_batting_avera=
ges_1877.jpg" class=3D"mw-file-description"><img src=3D"https://upload.wiki=
media.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/a/a0/National_League_batting_averages_187=
7.jpg/250px-National_League_batting_averages_1877.jpg" decoding=3D"async" w=
idth=3D"250" height=3D"213" class=3D"mw-file-element" data-file-width=3D"62=
2" data-file-height=3D"529"></a><figcaption>Top batting averages for the <a=
 href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/1877_Major_League_Baseball_season" t=
itle=3D"1877 Major League Baseball season">1877</a> season, as published in=
 <i>The Buffalo Sunday Morning News</i>=E2=80=94 <a href=3D"https://en.wiki=
pedia.org/wiki/Deacon_White" title=3D"Deacon White">Deacon White</a> led th=
e league</figcaption></figure>
<p><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Henry_Chadwick_(writer)" title=
=3D"Henry Chadwick (writer)">Henry Chadwick</a>, an English statistician ra=
ised on <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cricket" title=3D"Cricket"=
>cricket</a>, was an influential figure in the early history of baseball.<s=
up id=3D"cite_ref-1" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.or=
g/wiki/Batting_average_(baseball)#cite_note-1"><span class=3D"cite-bracket"=
>[</span>1<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> He is credited wi=
th creating the modern <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Box_score" =
title=3D"Box score">box score</a>, in 1859, and the practice of denoting a =
<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Strikeout" title=3D"Strikeout">str=
ikeout</a> with a "K".<sup id=3D"cite_ref-hall_2-0" class=3D"reference"><a =
href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Batting_average_(baseball)#cite_note-=
hall-2"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>2<span class=3D"cite-bracket">=
]</span></a></sup> Chadwick wrote in 1869: "In making up a score at the clo=
se of the match the record should be as follows:=E2=80=93Name of player, to=
tal number of times the first base was made by clean hits, total bases so m=
ade, left on bases after clean hits, and the number of times the first base=
 has been made on errors..."<sup id=3D"cite_ref-hersh_3-0" class=3D"referen=
ce"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Batting_average_(baseball)#cit=
e_note-hersh-3"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>3<span class=3D"cite-b=
racket">]</span></a></sup> This led to the recording of "clean" hits=E2=80=
=94times a batter reached base without benefit of an <a href=3D"https://en.=
wikipedia.org/wiki/Error_(baseball)" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Error (=
baseball)">error</a>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-hersh_3-1" class=3D"reference"><a =
href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Batting_average_(baseball)#cite_note-=
hersh-3"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>3<span class=3D"cite-bracket"=
>]</span></a></sup> In 1869, another early baseball proponent, Alfred Wrigh=
t, published an end-of-season summary that included the average number of t=
imes a batter had "clean" hits on a <i>per game</i> basis.<sup id=3D"cite_r=
ef-hersh_3-2" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/=
Batting_average_(baseball)#cite_note-hersh-3"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">=
[</span>3<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> In 1871, a writer =
for the <i><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/New_York_Clipper" title=
=3D"New York Clipper">New York Clipper</a></i>, Hervie Dobson, proposed tha=
t a batter's "average is found by dividing his total 'times first base on c=
lean hits' by his total number of times he went to the bat"=E2=80=94hits di=
vided by at bats.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-hersh_3-3" class=3D"reference"><a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Batting_average_(baseball)#cite_note-hers=
h-3"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>3<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</=
span></a></sup> By 1874, some teams were calculating batting averages, and =
by 1876, it was being calculated by all teams of the <a href=3D"https://en.=
wikipedia.org/wiki/National_League_(baseball)" title=3D"National League (ba=
seball)">National League</a>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-hersh_3-4" class=3D"refere=
nce"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Batting_average_(baseball)#ci=
te_note-hersh-3"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>3<span class=3D"cite-=
bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"Values">Values</h2><span cl=
ass=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a hr=
ef=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DBatting_average_(basebal=
l)&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D2" title=3D"Edit section: Values"><span>=
edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<figure class=3D"mw-default-size mw-halign-right" typeof=3D"mw:File/Thumb">=
<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:Josh_Gibson_1931.jpg" class=
=3D"mw-file-description"><img src=3D"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia=
/commons/thumb/7/75/Josh_Gibson_1931.jpg/242px-Josh_Gibson_1931.jpg" decodi=
ng=3D"async" width=3D"190" height=3D"262" class=3D"mw-file-element" data-fi=
le-width=3D"242" data-file-height=3D"334"></a><figcaption><a href=3D"https:=
//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Josh_Gibson" title=3D"Josh Gibson">Josh Gibson</a> =
has the highest major-league career batting average (.371). He is also the =
most recent player to hit .400 in a season (1943).</figcaption></figure>
<figure class=3D"mw-default-size mw-halign-right" typeof=3D"mw:File/Thumb">=
<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:Hugh_Duffy_Baseball.jpg" clas=
s=3D"mw-file-description"><img src=3D"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedi=
a/en/thumb/1/17/Hugh_Duffy_Baseball.jpg/250px-Hugh_Duffy_Baseball.jpg" deco=
ding=3D"async" width=3D"190" height=3D"169" class=3D"mw-file-element" data-=
