</figcaption></figure>
<p>In <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/1887_Major_League_Baseball_s=
eason" title=3D"1887 Major League Baseball season">1887</a>, <a href=3D"htt=
ps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Base_on_balls" title=3D"Base on balls">bases on =
balls</a> (walks) were counted as hits by the major leagues in existence at=
 the time. This inflated batting averages, with 11 players batting .400 or =
better, and the experiment was abandoned the following season. Historical s=
tatistics for the season were later revised, such that "Bases on balls shal=
l always be treated as neither a time at bat nor a hit for the batter."<sup=
 id=3D"cite_ref-20" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org=
/wiki/Batting_average_(baseball)#cite_note-20"><span class=3D"cite-bracket"=
>[</span>19<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading4"><h4 id=3D"1.000_career_average">1.000=
 career average</h4><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editse=
ction-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?titl=
e=3DBatting_average_(baseball)&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D4" title=3D"=
Edit section: 1.000 career average"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-=
editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p>In rare instances, players have concluded their careers with a perfect b=
atting average of 1.000=E2=80=94through the 2021 season, there were 94 such=
 players in major-league history, 83 of whom recorded exactly one hit in on=
e at bat.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-21" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.=
wikipedia.org/wiki/Batting_average_(baseball)#cite_note-21"><span class=3D"=
cite-bracket">[</span>20<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> Onl=
y one player with a 1.000 average has had three hits=E2=80=94outfielder <a =
href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/John_Paciorek" title=3D"John Paciorek=
">John Paciorek</a> (1963), who had three hits in three at bats; he also ha=
d two walks, and scored four runs.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-22" class=3D"referenc=
e"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Batting_average_(baseball)#cite=
_note-22"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>21<span class=3D"cite-bracke=
t">]</span></a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-23" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D=
"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Batting_average_(baseball)#cite_note-23"><sp=
an class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>22<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></=
a></sup> Players who had two hits in their only two at bats include: pitche=
r <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Frank_O%27Connor_(baseball)" tit=
le=3D"Frank O'Connor (baseball)">Frank O'Connor</a> (1893),<sup id=3D"cite_=
ref-24" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Battin=
g_average_(baseball)#cite_note-24"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>23<=
span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> catcher <a href=3D"https://e=
n.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mike_Hopkins_(baseball)" title=3D"Mike Hopkins (baseba=
ll)">Mike Hopkins</a> (1902),<sup id=3D"cite_ref-25" class=3D"reference"><a=
 href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Batting_average_(baseball)#cite_note=
-25"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>24<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]<=
/span></a></sup> pitcher <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Doc_Tonki=
n" title=3D"Doc Tonkin">Doc Tonkin</a> (1907),<sup id=3D"cite_ref-26" class=
=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Batting_average_(ba=
seball)#cite_note-26"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>25<span class=3D=
"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> pitcher <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.o=
rg/wiki/Hal_Deviney" title=3D"Hal Deviney">Hal Deviney</a> (1920),<sup id=
=3D"cite_ref-27" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wi=
ki/Batting_average_(baseball)#cite_note-27"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[<=
/span>26<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> pitcher <a href=3D"=
