<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"Qualifications_for_the_batt=
ing_title">Qualifications for the batting title</h2><span class=3D"mw-edits=
ection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://e=
n.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DBatting_average_(baseball)&amp;action=
=3Dedit&amp;section=3D5" title=3D"Edit section: Qualifications for the batt=
ing title"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</s=
pan></span></div>
<figure class=3D"mw-default-size mw-halign-right" typeof=3D"mw:File/Thumb">=
<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:1909_Ty_Cobb_Honus_Wagner.jpg=
" class=3D"mw-file-description"><img src=3D"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wi=
kipedia/commons/thumb/6/69/1909_Ty_Cobb_Honus_Wagner.jpg/250px-1909_Ty_Cobb=
_Honus_Wagner.jpg" decoding=3D"async" width=3D"190" height=3D"238" class=3D=
"mw-file-element" data-file-width=3D"1565" data-file-height=3D"1963"></a><f=
igcaption><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ty_Cobb" title=3D"Ty Cob=
b">Ty Cobb</a> (left) and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Honus_Wa=
gner" title=3D"Honus Wagner">Honus Wagner</a> in 1909</figcaption></figure>
<p>The MLB batting averages championships (often referred to as "<a href=3D=
"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/List_of_Major_League_Baseball_batting_champi=
ons" title=3D"List of Major League Baseball batting champions">the batting =
title</a>") are awarded annually to the player in each league with the high=
est batting average. <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ty_Cobb" titl=
e=3D"Ty Cobb">Ty Cobb</a> holds the MLB and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia=
.org/wiki/American_League" title=3D"American League">American League</a> (A=
L) record for most batting titles, officially winning 11 in his career.<sup=
 id=3D"cite_ref-BaseballRefBattingTitles2_33-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Batting_average_(baseball)#cite_note-Base=
ballRefBattingTitles2-33"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>32<span clas=
s=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> The <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.o=
rg/wiki/National_League_(baseball)" title=3D"National League (baseball)">Na=
tional League</a> (NL) record of eight batting titles is shared by <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Honus_Wagner" title=3D"Honus Wagner">Honu=
s Wagner</a> and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Tony_Gwynn" title=
=3D"Tony Gwynn">Tony Gwynn</a>. Most of Cobb's career and all of Wagner's c=
areer occurred during the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Dead-bal=
l_era" title=3D"Dead-ball era">dead-ball era</a>, which was characterized b=
y higher batting averages by star players (although the overall league batt=
ing average was historically at its lowest during that era) and much less p=
ower, whereas Gwynn's career took place in the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipe=
dia.org/wiki/Live-ball_era" title=3D"Live-ball era">live-ball era</a>.
</p><p>To determine which players are eligible to win the batting title, th=
e following conditions have been used over the sport's history:<sup id=3D"c=
ite_ref-34" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ba=
tting_average_(baseball)#cite_note-34"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span=
>33<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
<ul><li>Pre-1920 =E2=80=93 A player is required to appear in at least 100 g=
ames when the schedule was 154 games, and 90 games when the schedule was 14=
0 games. An exception to the rule was made for <a href=3D"https://en.wikipe=
dia.org/wiki/Ty_Cobb" title=3D"Ty Cobb">Ty Cobb</a> in 1914, who appeared i=
n 98 games but had a big lead and was also a favorite of American League Pr=
esident <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ban_Johnson" title=3D"Ban =
Johnson">Ban Johnson</a>.</li>
<li>1920=E2=80=931949 =E2=80=93 A player had to appear in 100 games to qual=
ify in the NL; the AL used 100 games from 1920 to 1935, and 400 at-bats fro=
m 1936 to 1949. The NL was advised to adopt 400 at-bats for the 1945 season=
, but National League President <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fo=
rd_Frick" title=3D"Ford Frick">Ford Frick</a> refused, feeling that 100 gam=
es should stand for the benefit of catchers and injured players. (<a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Taffy_Wright" title=3D"Taffy Wright">Taff=
y Wright</a> is often erroneously said to have been cheated out of the 1938=
 batting title; he batted .350 in exactly 100 games, with 263 ABs. <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Jimmie_Foxx" title=3D"Jimmie Foxx">Jimmie=
 Foxx</a> hit .349, in 149 games and 565 AB. But since the AL requirement t=
hat year was 400 at-bats, Foxx's batting title is undisputed.)</li>
<li>1950=E2=80=931956 =E2=80=93 A player needed 2.6 at-bats per team game o=
riginally scheduled. (With the 154-game schedule of the time, that meant a =
rounded-off 400 at-bats.) From 1951 to 1954, if the player with the highest=
 average in a league failed to meet the minimum at-bat requirement, the rem=
aining at-bats until qualification (e.g., five at-bats, if the player finis=
hed the season with 395 at-bats) were hypothetically considered hitless at-=
bats; if his recalculated batting average still topped the league, he was a=
warded the title. This standard was applied in the AL from 1936 to 1956.</l=
i>
<li>1957 to the present =E2=80=93 A player has needed 3.1 plate appearances=
 per team game originally scheduled; thus, players were no longer penalized=
 for walking so frequently or benefitted from walking so rarely. (In 1954, =
for example, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ted_Williams" title=
=3D"Ted Williams">Ted Williams</a> batted .345 but had only 386 ABs, while =
topping the AL with 136 walks. Williams thus lost the batting title to Clev=
eland's <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bobby_%C3%81vila" title=3D=
"Bobby =C3=81vila">Bobby =C3=81vila</a>, who hit .341 in 555 ABs.) In the 1=
54-game schedule, the required number of plate appearances was 477, and sin=
ce the era of the 162-game schedule, the requisite number of plate appearan=
ces has been 502. Adjustments to this figure were made during <a href=3D"ht=
tps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/MLB_lockout" title=3D"MLB lockout">strike-short=
ened seasons</a>, such as 1972, 1981, 1994, and 1995.</li></ul>
<p><span class=3D"anchor" id=3D"Tony_Gwynn_rule"></span>From 1967 to the pr=
esent, if the player with the highest average in a league does not meet the=
 minimum plate-appearance requirement, the remaining at-bats until qualific=
ation (e.g., five at-bats, if the player finished the season with 497 plate=
 appearances) are hypothetically considered hitless at-bats; if his recalcu=
lated batting average still tops the league, he is awarded the title. This =
is officially Rule 10.22(a), but it is also known as the "<a href=3D"https:=
//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Tony_Gwynn" title=3D"Tony Gwynn">Tony Gwynn</a> rul=
e" because the Padres' player won the batting crown in 1996 with a .353 ave=
rage on just 498 plate appearances (i.e., he was four short). Gwynn was awa=
rded the title since he would have led the league even if he had gone 0-for=
-4 in those missing plate appearances. His average would have dropped to .3=
49, five points better than second-place <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.or=
g/wiki/Ellis_Burks" title=3D"Ellis Burks">Ellis Burks</a>' .344.<sup id=3D"=
cite_ref-35" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/B=
atting_average_(baseball)#cite_note-35"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</spa=
n>34<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> In 2012, a one-time ame=
ndment to the rule was made to disqualify <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.o=
rg/wiki/Melky_Cabrera" title=3D"Melky Cabrera">Melky Cabrera</a> from the t=
itle. Cabrera requested that he be disqualified after serving a suspension =
that season for a positive <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Testost=
erone_(medication)" title=3D"Testosterone (medication)">testosterone</a> te=
st. He had batted .346 with 501 plate appearances, and the original rule wo=
uld have awarded him the title over <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wik=
i/San_Francisco_Giants" title=3D"San Francisco Giants">San Francisco Giants=
</a> teammate <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Buster_Posey" title=
=3D"Buster Posey">Buster Posey</a>, who won batting .336.<sup id=3D"cite_re=
f-36" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Batting_=
average_(baseball)#cite_note-36"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>35<sp=
an class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-37" class=
=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Batting_average_(ba=
seball)#cite_note-37"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>36<span class=3D=
"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
